KISS Principle (Keep It Simple, Stupid)

#Definition

	The KISS Principle states that systems and code should be kept as simple as possible, avoiding unnecessary complexity.
	Simpler designs are easier to understand, maintain, and extend.

#Objective

	1. Reduce unnecessary complexity
	2. Improve readability and maintainability
	3. Make debugging and testing easier

#Example – Violation of KISS
	class OrderProcessor {
	    public void processOrder(Order order) {
	        if(order != null && order.isValid()) {
	            if(order.getItems().size() > 0 && !order.isExpired() && order.getCustomer().isActive()) {
	                // complex nested logic
	                // send notifications, update inventory, apply discounts
	            }
	        }
	    }
	}


	Problem: Nested conditions and too many responsibilities make the code hard to read and maintain.
	
	Correct Implementation (Follows KISS)
	class OrderProcessor {
	    public void processOrder(Order order) {
	        if (!isOrderValid(order)) return;
	
	        processPayment(order);
	        updateInventory(order);
	        notifyCustomer(order);
	    }
	
	    private boolean isOrderValid(Order order) {
	        return order != null && order.isValid() && !order.isExpired() && order.hasItems() && order.getCustomer().isActive();
	    }
	
	    private void processPayment(Order order) { /* payment logic */ }
	    private void updateInventory(Order order) { /* inventory logic */ }
	    private void notifyCustomer(Order order) { /* notification logic */ }
	}
	
	
	✅ Responsibilities are clearly separated
	✅ Logic is simple and readable

#Real-World Analogy

	Using a Swiss Army knife for everything is complex.
	Using a simple, single-purpose tool for each task is easier and more effective.

#Benefits

	1. Easier to understand for new developers
	2. Fewer bugs and easier testing
	3. Easier to maintain and extend
	4. Encourages modular design

#Related Principles

	1. SRP (Single Responsibility Principle): Keeping things simple often aligns with having a single responsibility.
	2. DRY (Don’t Repeat Yourself): Simplicity reduces duplicate code and unnecessary abstraction.

